"1370","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","about 1377":"circa 1377","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Davenham, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1335–":"1335–Deceased","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1330–1373":"1330–1373","1360–1390":"1360–1390","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1377–1432":"1377–1432","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1 June 1370":"1 June 1370","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","about 1377":"about 1377","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Davenham, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Laughton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laughon","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Laughton  ."]},{"name":"Leighton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."]},{"name":"Lawton","meanings":["English:","habitational name, from Church Lawton in Cheshire, which is recorded as Lautune in 1086. The placename derives from Old English <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Laughton  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%